{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fba66f1b-1b97-4199-b32f-f63e29c2fd9c","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` alone isn't enough. You likely need to address these layers:\n\n**1. Hide Shell/Navigation chrome** (if applicable):\n```xml\nShell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\nShell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n```\n\n**2. iOS safe area (platform-specific):**\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\nios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n```\n\n**3. Ensure no padding/margin on the page or layout:**\n```xml\n<ContentPage Padding=\"0\" ...>\n    <Grid Margin=\"0\">\n        <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**4. Android – make system bars transparent** (in `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs` or styles):\n```csharp\nWindow.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\nWindow.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n```\n\nIn .NET 10 on Android 15+, edge-to-edge is enforced by default, but the bars may still have a scrim. Setting transparent colors + `UseSafeArea=\"False\"` on iOS is usually the missing piece.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e059bbed-cca7-4521-8244-3d8ebc8e719c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10, specifically wanting an image to fill behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common issue in .NET MAUI. Let me think about what they might be missing:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content that goes behind system bars, you typically need to:\n\n1. Set `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the page (which they've done)\n2. But more importantly, in .NET 10 / newer MAUI versions, there's the concept of edge-to-edge display that requires additional configuration.\n\n\n3. The real issue is likely that they need to set `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the Image control itself or its parent layout, since that property tells the layout system to disregard safe area insets. On iOS this extends content behind the safe areas, while on Android it handles system bars differently—especially important since Android 15 now enforces edge-to-edge by default. I'm realizing the platform-specific approach differs between iOS and Android—on iOS I need to use `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` to disable safe area constraints, while Android's edge-to-edge behavior is handled differently depending on the .NET version, and I should verify which method works best for .NET 10 specifically. I should also consider Shell and NavigationPage components that might be adding their own spacing, along with platform-specific settings like the Android status bar transparency and the Image's Aspect property—these are often the culprits when SafeAreaEdges alone doesn't work. For .NET 10 specifically, I'm thinking about how Android 15's edge-to-edge enforcement might require different configuration than earlier versions.","outputTokens":1548,"requestId":"080D:7CA0B:ACB0B9:C7BE81:69F2AAC2"},"id":"73323fb3-a19e-428b-a0c2-0a9039c08ae4","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:05:37.856Z","parentId":"29f2a222-9215-4af2-b30f-51411d0e37ab"}
